.TH TELEMON 1 "January 2025" "Telemon 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
telemon \- lightweight system health monitor with Telegram alerts
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B telemon
.RI [ options ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Telemon is a lightweight, self-managing system health monitor that sends Telegram alerts when system vitals change state.
It monitors CPU, memory, disk space, connectivity, and critical processes, but only alerts on actual state changes.
.PP
Designed for cron execution every 5 minutes, Telemon features:
.IP \(bu 2
Smart alerts with state-based deduplication
.IP \(bu 2
Configurable confirmation count to prevent false alarms
.IP \(bu 2
System vitals: CPU, memory, disk, internet connectivity
.IP \(bu 2
Process monitoring: system processes, Docker containers, PM2 processes
.IP \(bu 2
Website monitoring: HTTP/HTTPS endpoints, SSL certificate expiry
.IP \(bu 2
Self-rotating logs and persistent state across reboots
.SH CONFIGURATION
Configuration is stored in
.I .env
in the Telemon directory. Key settings:
.PP
.TS
tab(|);
l l.
TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN|Bot token from @BotFather
TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID|Your Telegram chat ID
CPU_THRESHOLD_WARN|CPU warning threshold (% of cores)
CPU_THRESHOLD_CRIT|CPU critical threshold (% of cores)
MEM_THRESHOLD_WARN|Memory warning threshold (% free)
MEM_THRESHOLD_CRIT|Memory critical threshold (% free)
DISK_THRESHOLD_WARN|Disk warning threshold (% used)
DISK_THRESHOLD_CRIT|Disk critical threshold (% used)
CONFIRMATION_COUNT|Consecutive checks before alerting
.TE
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.BI "bash telemon.sh"
Run a single check cycle manually
.TP
.BI "bash install.sh"
Install cron job and set up system integration
.TP
.BI "bash uninstall.sh "[\-\-full]
Remove cron job and optionally state/logs
.TP
.BI "bash update.sh "[\-\-check]
Update to latest version from git
.TP
.BI "bash telemon-admin.sh "command
Administration utility (backup, restore, status, validate)
.SH FILES
.TP
.I telemon.sh
Main monitoring script
.TP
.I .env
Configuration file (not in git)
.TP
.I telemon.log
Detailed check results and state changes
.TP
.I telemon_cron.log
Cron execution output
.TP
.I /tmp/telemon_sys_alert_state
State file for alert deduplication
.SH STATE MANAGEMENT
Telemon uses a state file to track the last known state of each check.
Format:
.PP
.EX
cpu=CRITICAL:3
mem=OK:0
disk_root=WARNING:1
.EE
.PP
The count indicates how many consecutive checks have shown this state.
Alerts only fire when the count reaches CONFIRMATION_COUNT.
.SH ALERT BEHAVIOR
.TS
tab(|);
l l.
First run|Bootstrap message with all metrics
State unchanged|Silent (no message)
OK → WARNING|Alert after confirmation count
OK → CRITICAL|Alert after confirmation count
CRITICAL → OK|Resolution alert
WARNING → OK|Resolution alert
.TE
.SH EXAMPLES
Run manually:
.PP
.EX
bash telemon.sh
.EE
.PP
View recent logs:
.PP
.EX
tail -f telemon.log
.EE
.PP
Reset state (forces fresh alerts):
.PP
.EX
rm /tmp/telemon_sys_alert_state
.EE
.PP
Create backup:
.PP
.EX
bash telemon-admin.sh backup
.EE
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Successful execution
.TP
.B 1
Configuration error or fatal issue
.TP
.B 2
Some checks failed (but execution completed)
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B SCRIPT_DIR
Directory containing telemon.sh (auto-detected)
.TP
.B STATE_FILE
Path to state file (default: /tmp/telemon_sys_alert_state)
.TP
.B LOG_FILE
Path to log file (default: ./telemon.log)
.SH NOTES
Telemon is designed for Linux systems and uses Linux-specific /proc filesystem interfaces:
.IP \(bu 2
/proc/loadavg for CPU load
.IP \(bu 2
/proc/meminfo for memory statistics
.IP \(bu 2
/proc/swaps for swap usage
.IP \(bu 2
/proc/stat for I/O wait metrics
